Data Preparation¶

This dataset contains x-rays of pediatric patients aged 1-5 years old from the Guangzhou Women and Children's Medical Center in Guangzhou, China. The x-rays are either labeled as having pneumonia or not having pneumonia (normal). A machine learning model on this dataset could be used to screen patients for pneumonia prior to seeing a medical professional. This could help reduce the number of patients the doctors have to see about pneumonia.

Link to dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/tolgadincer/labeled-chest-xray-images

# Directory containing images data
data_dir = "../Datasets/chest_xray/train"
# Subdirectories with normal and pneumonia images
categories = ["NORMAL", "PNEUMONIA"]
# Size to resize images to
size = (50, 50)

labels = []
labels_binary = []
images = []
for i, cat in enumerate(categories):
    # For each label, create path to subdirectory
    path = os.path.join(data_dir, cat)
    for file in os.listdir(path):
        # Read and resize all images in subdirectory
        labels.append(cat)
        labels_binary.append(i)
        img = cv2.imread(os.path.join(path, file), cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE)
        img = cv2.resize(img, size)
        images.append(img)

labels_binary = list(np.argmax(keras.utils.to_categorical(labels_binary, 2), axis = 1))

# a helper plotting function
def plot_gallery(images, titles, h, w, n_row=3, n_col=6):
    """Helper function to plot a gallery of portraits"""
    plt.figure(figsize=(1.7 * n_col, 2.3 * n_row))
    plt.subplots_adjust(bottom=0, left=.01, right=.99, top=.90, hspace=.35)
    for i in range(n_row * n_col):
        plt.subplot(n_row, n_col, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(images[i].reshape((h, w)), cmap=plt.cm.gray)
        plt.title(titles[i], size=12)
        plt.xticks(())
        plt.yticks(())

Evaluation Criteria¶

In this business case, where a positive outcome is having pneumonia, it is much more important to minimize false negatives than false positives. If there is a false positive, someone will see a doctor but would not receive treatment after the doctor diagnoses them. Very little harm is done in this case, except for wasting a little bit of the doctor and patient's time. If there is a false negative, someone who has pneumonia will not receive the treatment that they need. To prioritize minimizing false negatives, we will use recall as our evalutation criteria.

Training/Testing Split¶

We can use K-Fold cross validation with 10 folds so that every instance is used in both the training and testing sets and give us a 90/10 training/testing split in every set. To account for the potential noise in a single K-Fold run, we will use 3 repeats. To maintain the relative class frequency in the testing data, we will stratify the folds by the outcome and then oversample the training data in each split. Oversampling the training data in each split will prevent the model from prioritizing one class over another, but maintaining the relative class frequencies in the testing data will make sure the model evaluation is similar to what a deployed model will see with new data.

In [9]:
cv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits = 10, n_repeats = 3, random_state = 7324)
data_split = []
y_test_folds = []
y_test = []
for train, test in cv.split(images, labels_binary):
    train_norm = list(train[train < pneum_index])
    train_pneum = list(train[train >= pneum_index])
    indices = np.random.randint(len(train_norm), size = len(train_pneum) - len(train_norm))
    for i in indices:
        train_norm.append(i)
        
    train_indices = train_norm + train_pneum
    data_split.append((
        (np.array(images)[train_indices], np.array(labels_binary)[train_indices]), 
        (np.array(images)[test], np.array(labels_binary)[test])
    ))
    
    y_test_folds.append(np.array(labels_binary)[test])
    for label in np.array(labels_binary)[test]:
        y_test.append(label)

Modeling¶

Model 1 (Architecture 1, Parameter Set 1)¶

In [10]:
def create_model(num_filter_layers, kernel_size, pool_size, neurons = []):
    cnn = Sequential()
    
    cnn.add(RandomBrightness(factor = 0.1))

    for num_filters in num_filter_layers:
        cnn.add( 
            Conv2D(
                filters=num_filters, 
                kernel_size=kernel_size, 
                padding='same'
            ) 
        )
        cnn.add(Activation('relu'))
        cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=pool_size))

    # add one layer on flattened output
    cnn.add(Flatten())
    for n in neurons:
        cnn.add(Dense(n, activation = "relu"))
    cnn.add(Dense(1, activation = "sigmoid"))

    # Let's train the model 
    cnn.compile(
        loss='binary_crossentropy',
        optimizer='rmsprop',
        metrics=[Recall(name = "recall")]
    )

    input_shape = [None, h, w, 1]
    cnn.build(input_shape)
    
    return cnn

Our first CNN architecture has 2 convolutional layers and only 1 dense layer with a sigmoid activation at the end with a single neuron for the binary classification. Each convolutional layer has 16 filters.

yhat_proba_arch1_param1_folds = []
history_arch1_param1 = {
    "recall": [],
    "val_recall": [],
    "loss": [],
    "val_loss": []
}

# Iterate through cross validation folds
for i, (train, test) in enumerate(data_split):
    # Print fold number
    sys.stderr.write('\rRepeat: {}/{}, Fold: {}/{} '.format(int(i / 10) + 1, 3, (i % 10) + 1, 10))
    sys.stderr.flush()
    
    # Fit model
    history = cnn_arch1_param1.fit(
        train[0], 
        train[1], 
        batch_size=32, 
        epochs=15, 
        shuffle=True, 
        verbose=0,
        validation_data=(test[0], test[1])
    )
            
    # Store model history
    history_arch1_param1["recall"].append(history.history["recall"])
    history_arch1_param1["val_recall"].append(history.history["val_recall"])
    history_arch1_param1["loss"].append(history.history["loss"])
    history_arch1_param1["val_loss"].append(history.history["val_loss"])
    
    # Store model predicted probabilities
    yhat_proba_arch1_param1_folds.append(cnn_arch1_param1.predict(test[0], verbose = 0))
    
# Merge predicted probabilities for all folds
yhat_proba_arch1_param1 = [ prob[0] for probs in yhat_proba_arch1_param1_folds for prob in probs ]
yhat_arch1_param1 = np.round(yhat_proba_arch1_param1) # round to get binary class
yhat_arch1_param1_folds = list(map(lambda x: np.round(x)[:,0], yhat_proba_arch1_param1_folds))
# Take the mean of all history values for each epoch
for key in history_arch1_param1.keys():
    history_arch1_param1[key] = np.mean(history_arch1_param1[key], axis = 0)

In [15]:
def compare_models(y, yhat):
    num_models = len(yhat)
    if num_models > 2:
        num_rows = 2
        plt.figure(figsize = (15, 10))
    else:
        num_rows = 1
        plt.figure(figsize = (15, 5))
    num_cols = num_models // num_rows
    if num_rows * num_cols < num_models:
        num_cols += 1
    for i in range(num_models):
        acc = mt.accuracy_score(y, yhat[i])
        recall = mt.recall_score(y, yhat[i])
        plt.subplot(num_rows, num_cols, i+1)
        cm = mt.confusion_matrix(y, yhat[i])
        cm = cm / np.sum(cm, axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='.4f', xticklabels=categories, yticklabels=categories)
        plt.title(f'Model {i+1}: Accuracy = {acc:.4f}, Recall = {recall:.4f}')
        plt.xlabel("Predicted Class")
        plt.ylabel("Actual Class")

The 2 CNN architecture has 3 convolutional layers instead of 2 and has 2 additional dense layers. Each convolutional layer has 16 neurons and the additional dense layers have 250 and 100 neurons with a relu activation.

Model Comparison¶

The heatmaps above show that the model accuracy and recall is fairly similar for all of the models (all scores are greater than 0.99). However, we can find a confidence interval for the mean difference in recall score for the folds between two models to determine if one model performs better than another. Since there are 30 total folds (10 folds in each of the 3 repeats), we will use a t-distribution with 29 degrees of freedom and a 95% confidence level to compute the confidence interval.

In [84]:
# Function that returns the 95% confidence interval for folded comparison of two models
def folded_comparison(y, yhat1, yhat2, scorer):
    recall1 = np.zeros(len(y))
    recall2 = np.zeros(len(y))
    for i in range(len(y)):
        recall1[i] = scorer(y[i], yhat1[i])
        recall2[i] = scorer(y[i], yhat2[i])
    
    t = 2.045 / np.sqrt(len(y))
    e = recall2 - recall1
    sd = np.std(e)
    dbar = np.mean(e)
    
    lower = dbar - t * sd
    upper = dbar + t * sd
    
    return (lower, upper)

All of the confidence intervals above have the lower bound less than 0 and the upper bound greater than 0 except for models 2 and 4. This means that at the 95% confidence level, there is not a significant difference in the recall scores for any of the models, except models 2 and 4. Model 4 has a higher recall score than model 2, so we can conclude that model 4 is better than model 2. However, we cannot conclude that model 4 is better than either model 1 or model 3. Since none of the models can be considered the "best" model based on these confidence intervals, we can repeat these confidence intervals with the precision score instead of recall. We are only considering precision score because there is not significant difference in the recall scores.

ResNet expects images with 3 channels as inputs, so we will ad a convolutional layer with 3 filters to the beginning of the network to add the required channels to our images. We will then send the convolved images into the pre-trained ResNet network and end with 2 dense layers. The first layer has 10 neurons with a relu activation and the final layer has 1 neuron with a sigmoid activation to make our binary classification.

In [44]:
pretrained = Sequential()

pretrained.add( 
    Conv2D(
        filters=3, 
        kernel_size=(3,3), 
        padding='same',
    ) 
)

pretrained.add(resnet)
pretrained.add(Dense(10, activation = "relu"))
pretrained.add(Dense(1, activation = "sigmoid"))

# Let's train the model 
pretrained.compile(
    loss='binary_crossentropy',
    optimizer='rmsprop',
    metrics=[Recall(name = "recall")]
)

input_shape = [None, h, w, 1]
pretrained.build(input_shape)

pretrained.summary()

%%time

yhat_proba_pretrained_folds = []
history_pretrained = {
    "recall": [],
    "val_recall": [],
    "loss": [],
    "val_loss": []
}

# Iterate through cross validation folds
for i, (train, test) in enumerate(data_split):
    # Print fold number
    sys.stderr.write('\rRepeat: {}/{}, Fold: {}/{} '.format(int(i / 10) + 1, 3, (i % 10) + 1, 10))
    sys.stderr.flush()
    
    # Fit model
    history = pretrained.fit(
        train[0], 
        train[1], 
        batch_size=32, 
        epochs=5, 
        shuffle=True, 
        verbose=0,
        validation_data=(test[0], test[1])
    )
            
    # Store model history
    history_pretrained["recall"].append(history.history["recall"])
    history_pretrained["val_recall"].append(history.history["val_recall"])
    history_pretrained["loss"].append(history.history["loss"])
    history_pretrained["val_loss"].append(history.history["val_loss"])
    
    # Store model predicted probabilities
    yhat_proba_pretrained_folds.append(pretrained.predict(test[0], verbose = 0))
    
# Merge predicted probabilities for all folds
yhat_proba_pretrained = [ prob[0] for probs in yhat_proba_pretrained_folds for prob in probs ]
yhat_pretrained = np.round(yhat_proba_pretrained) # round to get binary class
yhat_pretrained_folds = list(map(lambda x: np.round(x)[:,0], yhat_proba_pretrained_folds))
# Take the mean of all history values for each epoch
for key in history_pretrained.keys():
    history_pretrained[key] = np.mean(history_pretrained[key], axis = 0)

The ResNet network significantly increases the training time, so the network was only trained with 5 epochs for this lab. It is difficult to tell with if the model has converged or not with only 5 epochs. With more time, I would experiment with more epochs to find the best number of epochs before deploying a model.
